[[ja:闇御津羽神]]
[[sn:Kuramitsuha]]

[[Image:Descendants of Izanagi and Izanami.svg|thumb|right|250px|Myth of the Generation of Gods (the gods born of Izanagi and Izanami) ]]
'''Kuramitsuha''' (闇御津羽神) is a {{ill|God (Shinto)|ja|神 (神道)|lt=God|lt_ja=神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/God (Shinto)|qq=}} appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese mythology|qq=}}.

In {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}, it is written as '''闇御津羽神''', and in {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, as '''闇罔象神'''.

== Mythology ==
In {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese mythology|qq=}}, during the {{ill|Birth of the Gods|ja|神産み|lt=Divine Birth|lt_ja=神産み|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Birth of the Gods|qq=}}, it is said that {{ill|Izanagi no Mikoto|ja|伊邪那岐命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi no Mikoto|qq=}} slew {{ill|Hinokagutsuchi|ja|火之迦具土神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hinokagutsuchi|qq=}}, and thus Kuramitsuha was born.

In one version from the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, the blood that accumulated on the hilt of the sword used to cut Kagutsuchi—leaking from between the fingers—gave rise to {{ill|Yamiokami|ja|淤加美神|lt=Yami Okami|lt_ja=闇淤加美神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamiokami|qq=}} along with the birth of '''闇御津羽神'''. In another version of the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, one of the three deities produced by the slaying of 軻遇突智命 is identified as '''Taka{{lang|zh|龗}}神''' (たかおかみのかみ).

In another account, three deities are born, including {{ill|Kurayamatsumi|ja|闇山津見神|lt=Kurayama-tsumi|lt_ja=闇山祇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurayamatsumi|qq=}} (くらやまつみ).

== Overview ==
The term "Yami" (闇) means "dark" and refers to a dim valley, while "Mitsuha" (ミツハ) derives from "hayai mizu" (水早) and signifies the initial flow of water. This is synonymous in meaning with the "Mitsuha" of {{ill|Yatohanamonomi no Kami|ja|弥都波能売神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yatohanamonomi no Kami|qq=}}.<ref>新潮社古典集成　古事記</ref>

Yamimitsuhaga no Kami is the deity presiding over the emerging waters of a gorge.

Like '''Yami{{lang|zh|龗}}神''' and '''Taka{{lang|zh|龗}}神''', it is also considered a {{ill|Dragon deity|ja|竜|lt=Dragon god|lt_ja=龍|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dragon deity|qq=}}. Dragons are revered as deities governing water and {{ill|Rain|ja|雨|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rain|qq=}}. Consequently, Yamimōshōjin is venerated as the deity of {{ill|Rainmaking|ja|雨乞い|lt=Pray for rain|lt_ja=祈雨|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rainmaking|qq=}}, rain cessation (しう), {{ill|Irrigation|ja|灌漑|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Irrigation|qq=}}, and wells.

At Kakuru Shrine (located in {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shizuoka Prefecture|qq=}} and {{ill|Hamamatsu City|ja|浜松市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hamamatsu City|qq=}}), it is enshrined together with Yami{{lang|zh|龗}}神.

